abstract = {The effect of isobaric cooling (over the range 190-350\~{}K) and isothermal compression (up to 700\~{}MPa) on structural a-\~{}and secondary b-relaxations has been studied for low molecular weight glass-forming systems. The shape of the a-loss peak was found to change with temperature T and pressure P but to be constant for a combination of T and P giving the same ta(T,P). The invariance of shape at constant ta(T,P) involved also the excess wing, i.e.\~{}the process showing up at the high-frequency tail of the a-loss peak in systems with no well-resolved b-process. Likewise, systems where the excess wing evolved to a well-resolved b-peak showed that the timescale of the b-process was strongly related to that of the a-peak. Also in this case, once a given value ta(T,P) was fixed, a corresponding value tb(T,P) was found for different T and P. Same results were found also for a binary mixture of a polar rigid molecule dissolved in an apolar solvent, i.e.\~{}a model system for Johari-Goldstein intermolecular relaxation. These evidences imply that a strong correlation exists between structural a-\~{}and Johari-Goldstein relaxation over a wide interval of temperature and density.},
